[src:buildah/container-virtualization] In software engineering, **containerization** is operating-system-level virtualization or application-level virtualization over multiple resources so that software applications can run in isolated user spaces called *containers* in any cloud or non-cloud environment, regardless of type or vendor.
[src:buildah/container-virtualization] The term "container" has different meanings in different contexts, and it is important to ensure that the intended definition aligns with the audience's understanding.
[src:buildah/container-virtualization] Each *container* is basically a fully functional and portable cloud or non-cloud computing environment surrounding the application and keeping it independent of other environments running in parallel.
[src:buildah/container-virtualization] Individually, each container simulates a different software application and runs isolated processes by bundling related configuration files, libraries and dependencies.
[src:buildah/container-virtualization] But, collectively, multiple containers share a common operating system kernel (OS).
[src:buildah/container-virtualization] In recent times, containerization technology has been widely adopted by cloud computing platforms like Amazon Web Services, Microsoft Azure, Google Cloud Platform, and IBM Cloud.
[src:buildah/container-virtualization] Containerization has also been pursued by the U.S.
[src:buildah/container-virtualization] Department of Defense as a way of more rapidly developing and fielding software updates, with first application in its F-22 air superiority fighter.
[src:buildah/container-virtualization] Container orchestration or container management is mostly used in the context of application containers.
[src:buildah/container-virtualization] Implementations providing such orchestration include Kubernetes and Docker swarm.
[src:buildah/container-virtualization] This includes functionality to create a cluster, to upgrade the software or repair it, balance the load between existing instances, scale by starting or stopping instances to adapt to the number of users, to log activities and monitor produced logs or the application itself by querying sensors.
[src:buildah/container-virtualization] Open-source implementations of such software include OKD and Rancher.
[src:buildah/container-virtualization] Quite a number of companies provide container cluster management as a managed service, like Alibaba, Amazon, Google, and Microsoft.
[src:buildah/dockerfile] The core software that runs and manages these containers is called **Docker Engine**.
[src:buildah/dockerfile] Docker was first released in 2013 and continues to be developed by Docker, Inc.
[src:buildah/dockerfile] The platform includes both free and paid tiers.
[src:buildah/dockerfile] Solomon Hykes started the Docker project in France as an internal project within dotCloud, a platform-as-a-service company.
[src:buildah/dockerfile] dotCloud Inc. was founded by Kamel Founadi, Hykes, and Sebastien Pahl during the Y Combinator Summer 2010 startup incubator group and launched in 2011, and renamed to Docker Inc in 2013.
[src:buildah/dockerfile] Docker debuted to the public in Santa Clara at PyCon in 2013.
[src:buildah/dockerfile] It was released as open-source in March 2013.
[src:buildah/dockerfile] At the time, it used LXC as its default execution environment.
[src:buildah/dockerfile] One year later, with the release of version 0.9, Docker replaced LXC with its own component, *libcontainer*, which was written in the Go programming language.
[src:buildah/dockerfile] In 2017, Docker created the Moby project for open research and development.
[src:buildah/dockerfile] In March 2026, the Communications of the ACM featured Docker as the cover article in a retrospective article of the past decade.
[src:buildah/dockerfile] Containers are isolated from one another and bundle their own software, libraries and configuration files; they can communicate with each other through well-defined channels.
[src:buildah/dockerfile] Because all of the containers share the services of a single operating system kernel, they use fewer resources than virtual machines.
[src:buildah/dockerfile] Docker can package an application and its dependencies in a virtual container that can, in principle, run on any Linux, Windows, or macOS computer.
[src:buildah/dockerfile] This enables the application to run in a variety of locations, such as on-premises, in public *(see decentralized computing, distributed computing, and cloud computing)* or private cloud.
[src:buildah/dockerfile] Docker on macOS uses a Linux virtual machine to run the containers.
[src:buildah/dockerfile] Because Docker containers are lightweight, a single server or virtual machine can run several containers simultaneously.
[src:buildah/dockerfile] A 2018 analysis found that a typical Docker use case involves running eight containers per host, and that a quarter of analyzed organizations run 18 or more per host.
[src:buildah/dockerfile] It can also be installed on a single board computer like the Raspberry Pi.
[src:buildah/dockerfile] The Linux kernel's support for namespaces mostly isolates an application's view of the operating environment, including process trees, network, user IDs and mounted file systems, while the kernel's cgroups provide resource limiting for memory and CPU.
[src:buildah/dockerfile] Since version 0.9, Docker includes its own component (called libcontainer) to use virtualization facilities provided directly by the Linux kernel, in addition to using abstracted virtualization interfaces via libvirt, LXC and systemd-nspawn.
[src:buildah/dockerfile] Docker implements a high-level API to provide lightweight containers that run processes in isolation.
[src:buildah/dockerfile] , is a persistent process that manages Docker containers and handles container objects.
[src:buildah/dockerfile] The daemon listens for requests that are sent via the Docker Engine API.
[src:buildah/dockerfile] (CLI) that allows users to interact with Docker daemons.
[src:buildah/dockerfile] Docker objects are various entities used to assemble an application in Docker.
[src:buildah/dockerfile] The main classes of Docker objects are images, containers, and services.
[src:buildah/dockerfile] A Docker registry is a repository for Docker images.
[src:buildah/dockerfile] Docker clients connect to registries to download ("pull") images for use or upload ("push") images that they have built.
[src:buildah/dockerfile] Docker Hub is the default registry where Docker looks for images.
[src:buildah/dockerfile] Docker registries also allow the creation of notifications based on events.
[src:buildah/dockerfile] A Dockerfile is a text file that commonly specifies several aspects of a Docker container: the Linux distribution, installation commands for the programming language runtime environment and application source code.
[src:buildah/open-container-initiative] The **Open Container Initiative** (**OCI**) is a Linux Foundation project, started in June 2015 by Docker, CoreOS, and the maintainers of appc (short for "App Container") to design open standards for operating system-level virtualization (containers).
[src:buildah/open-container-initiative] At launch, OCI was focused on Linux containers and subsequent work has extended it to other operating systems.
[src:buildah/open-container-initiative] There are currently three OCI specifications in development and use: the *Runtime Specification* (runtime-spec), the *Image Specification* (image-spec), and the *Distribution Specification* (distribution-spec).
[src:buildah/open-container-initiative] The OCI Image Format Project was split out from the Runtime Project into its own specification on March 23, 2016.
[src:buildah/open-container-initiative] The image-spec is a software shipping container image format spec (OCI Image Format) that reached version 1.0.0 on July 19, 2017.
[src:buildah/open-container-initiative] The OCI Distribution Spec Project defines the distribution-spec, an API protocol to facilitate and standardize the distribution of content.
[src:buildah/open-container-initiative] The distribution-spec was created on March 8, 2018, from a Proposal for a JSON Registry API V2.1.
[src:buildah/open-container-initiative] The distribution-spec reached version 1.0.0 on April 26, 2021.
[src:buildah/os-level-virtualization] On Unix-like operating systems, this feature can be seen as an advanced implementation of the standard chroot mechanism, which changes the apparent root folder for the current running process and its children.
[src:buildah/os-level-virtualization] In addition to isolation mechanisms, the kernel often provides resource-management features to limit the impact of one container's activities on other containers.
[src:buildah/os-level-virtualization] Linux containers are all based on the virtualization, isolation, and resource management mechanisms provided by the Linux kernel, notably Linux namespaces and cgroups.
[src:buildah/os-level-virtualization] Although the word *container* most commonly refers to OS-level virtualization, it is sometimes used to refer to fuller virtual machines operating in varying degrees of concert with the host OS, such as Microsoft's Hyper-V containers.
[src:buildah/os-level-virtualization] For an overview of virtualization since 1960, see Timeline of virtualization technologies.
[src:buildah/os-level-virtualization] On ordinary operating systems for personal computers, a computer program can see (even though it might not be able to access) all the system's resources.
[src:buildah/os-level-virtualization] The operating system may allow or deny access to such resources based on which program requests them and the user account in the context in which it runs.
[src:buildah/os-level-virtualization] The operating system may also hide those resources, so that when the computer program enumerates them, they do not appear in the enumeration results.
[src:buildah/os-level-virtualization] Nevertheless, from a programming point of view, the computer program has interacted with those resources and the operating system has managed an act of interaction.
[src:buildah/os-level-virtualization] With operating-system-virtualization, or containerization, it is possible to run programs within containers, to which only parts of these resources are allocated.
[src:buildah/os-level-virtualization] A program expecting to see the whole computer, once run inside a container, can only see the allocated resources and believes them to be all that is available.
[src:buildah/os-level-virtualization] Several containers can be created on each operating system, to each of which a subset of the computer's resources is allocated.
[src:buildah/os-level-virtualization] Each container may contain any number of computer programs.
[src:buildah/os-level-virtualization] These programs may run concurrently or separately, and may even interact with one another.
[src:buildah/os-level-virtualization] Containerization has similarities to application virtualization: In the latter, only one computer program is placed in an isolated container and the isolation applies to file system only.
[src:buildah/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system level virtualization is commonly used in virtual hosting environments, where it is useful for securely allocating finite hardware resources among a large number of mutually-distrusting users.
[src:buildah/os-level-virtualization] System administrators may also use it for consolidating server hardware by moving services on separate hosts into containers on the one server.
[src:buildah/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system level virtualization can also be used to run software created for a certain Linux distribution on another distribution, an example is Distrobox.
[src:buildah/os-level-virtualization] Other typical scenarios include separating several programs to separate containers for improved security, hardware independence, and added resource management features.
[src:buildah/os-level-virtualization] The improved security provided by the use of a chroot mechanism, however, is not perfect.
[src:buildah/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system-level virtualization implementations capable of live migration can also be used for dynamic load balancing of containers between nodes in a cluster.
[src:buildah/os-level-virtualization] This form of virtualization also does not require hardware support for efficient performance.
[src:buildah/os-level-virtualization] Operating-system level virtualization is not as flexible as other virtualization approaches since it cannot host a guest operating system different from the host one, or a different guest kernel.
[src:buildah/os-level-virtualization] For example, with Linux, different distributions are fine, but other operating systems such as Windows cannot be hosted.
[src:buildah/os-level-virtualization] Operating systems using variable input systematics are subject to limitations within the virtualized architecture.
[src:buildah/os-level-virtualization] Adaptation methods including cloud-server relay analytics maintain the OS-level virtual environment within these applications.
[src:buildah/os-level-virtualization] Solaris partially overcomes the limitation described above with its branded zones feature, which provides the ability to run an environment within a container that emulates an older Solaris 8 or 9 version in a Solaris 10 host.
[src:buildah/os-level-virtualization] However, in 2010 Linux branded zones were removed from Solaris; in 2014 they were reintroduced in Illumos, which is the open source Solaris fork, supporting 32-bit Linux kernels.
[src:buildah/os-level-virtualization] Some implementations provide file-level copy-on-write (CoW) mechanisms.
[src:buildah/os-level-virtualization] (Most commonly, a standard file system is shared between partitions, and those partitions that change the files automatically create their own copies.) This is easier to back up, more space-efficient and simpler to cache than the block-level copy-on-write schemes common on whole-system virtualizers.
[src:buildah/os-level-virtualization] Whole-system virtualizers, however, can work with non-native file systems and create and roll back snapshots of the entire system state.
